summary:
Determining the situation in Somalia remains a threat to international peace and security,

Acting under Chapter VII,

1. Requests the Secretary-General to continue and intensify efforts to promote an inclusive political process in Somalia;
2. Supports the Secretary-General's approach, as outlined in his 14 March 2008 report, and requests an updated comprehensive strategy within 60 days;
3. Approves the establishment of a joint planning unit to facilitate strategy implementation;
4. Welcomes the relocation of UNPOS and the country team headquarters from Nairobi to Mogadishu or an interim location in Somalia;
5. Requests the Secretary-General to report on progress towards developing a constitution, holding a constitutional referendum, and free and democratic elections in 2009;
6. Intends to take measures against those who prevent a peaceful political process or threaten the Transitional Federal Institutions (TFIs) or African Union Mission in Somalia (AMISOM);
7. Intends to strengthen the arms embargo and take measures against those who breach it;
8. Requests contingency planning for a possible United Nations peacekeeping operation to succeed AMISOM;
9. Welcomes additional United Nations technical advisers to the African Union's Strategic Plans and Management Unit;
10. Reiterates its call for financial resources, personnel, equipment, and services for AMISOM's full deployment.
Here is a summarized version of the Security Council document:

11. Supports States' contributions to protect World Food Programme convoys, calls on States and regional organizations to protect shipping involved in humanitarian aid to Somalia and UN-authorized activities, and requests the Secretary-General to provide support.

12. Supports humanitarian relief efforts in Somalia, recalls resolution 1502 (2003) on protecting humanitarian and UN personnel, and demands all parties ensure safe and unhindered access for humanitarian assistance.

13. Requests the Secretary-General to establish a UN-led mechanism to facilitate consultations between humanitarian organizations, the Transitional Federal Government (TFG), donors, and other parties to resolve issues of access, security, and humanitarian relief.

14. Requests the Secretary-General to establish a capacity within the UN Political Office for Somalia (UNPOS) to monitor and enhance human rights protection in Somalia.
